  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, which include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training staff on AML regulations\n- Implementing screening processes\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting customer information\n- Assessing risk levels\n- Ongoing customer monitoring\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Following global AML standards\n- Cooperating with law enforcement\n- Adhering to regulations like Bank Secrecy Act\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Implementing risk mitigation strategies\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n\n7. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Regulatory sanctions\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and ensure transparency in financial transactions.",
